Project 5, Partial Differential Equations cont'd¶

Devon DeJohn | PHY 4611 | April 22, 2019

This project includes the various numerical methods developed so far, with the addition of a few more, in solving the linear advection equation. We start with the familar, and most basic marching method FTCS from the previous project. We show that it is unstable for all values of $\tau$, and incorrectly distorts our initial gaussian wave pulse. We then explore several different numerical 'relaxations', and finish with the transport equation, wherein a delta spike diffuses during advection.

7.2 Dirichlet advection of sinusoidal boundary condition¶

Modify advect to use the Dirichlet boundary conditions

$$\begin{align*} a(x=-L/2,t) &= sin(\omega t) \\ a(x=L/2,t) &= 0 \end{align*}$$

Run the program long enough for the generated wave to traverse the system. Using $N=50$ grid points and a frequency of $\omega=10\pi$, what do you observe for time steps of $\tau = 0.015 \,,\, 0.02$ and $0.03$? How do your results change when you vary the frequency? Test each case using the FTCS, Lax, and Lax-Wendroff schemes.

For all values of $\tau$, the FTCS scheme completely fails to produce a solution. Lax plots quite well for $\tau=0.2$ but explodes exponentially for $\tau=0.03$ and incorrectly distorts for $\tau=0.015$, although in this case at least retains the general structure of the real solution. Lax-Wendroff performs similarly where the $\tau=0.015$ and $\tau=0.02$ produce solutions, however the former also incorrectly decays near the end of the integration. For $\tau=0.03$, Lax-Wendroff also explodes exponentially.

Changing frequency did not have an effect on any of the FTCS trials. Increasing the frequency of the generated wave tended to cause instability in both Lax and Lax-Wendroff, while lowering the frequency had the opposite effect, which is reasonable as these numerical methods seem to struggle to maintain stability across grid points where the amplitude of the advection equation changes too quickly. Even decreasing $\tau$ by an order of magnitude still does not produce an accurate solution for a frequency of $\omega=25 \, \pi$, an increase of only 2.5x. These methods are very picky in their parameters.

7.3 Discretize the transport equation¶

Derive the transport equation

$$\frac{\partial T}{\partial t} = -c \frac{\partial T}{\partial x} + \kappa \frac{\partial ^2 T}{\partial x^2}$$

using a pencil and solve.

I discretized using the forward derivative for the temporal term, and the centered derivative for the spatial second derivative to obtain:

$$T_i^{n+1} = -\frac{c \tau}{h} (T_{i+1}^{n} - T_{i}^{n}) + \frac{\kappa \tau}{h^2} (T_{i+1}^{n} + T_{i-1}^{n} - 2 T_{i}^{n}) + T_{i}^{n}$$

I then simplified the expression and combined like-terms so that in my implementation in exercise 7.4 the elements of each row are only evaluated once.

7.4 Implement discretized transport equation¶

Write a program that uses the FTCS scheme to solve the one-dimensional transport equation from the previous exercise. Empirally show that the numerical solution is stable if

$$\bigg{(}\frac{c\tau}{h}\bigg{)}^2 \leq \frac{2 \kappa \tau}{h^2} \leq 1$$

I discuss my implementation in the previous exercise. I found the surface plot for the transport equation somewhat lacking so I also included a contour plot in which the advection and diffusion are very clearly shown.

I also print values for the two conditions for stability, and whether the solution is expected to be stable. I found that as $2 \kappa \tau / h^2$ approaches the upper bound, the solution actually becomes unstable despite the fact that Garcia claims $2 \kappa \tau / h^2$ can equal $1$. For $\tau = 0.002825 \,,\, N = 50$ the middle term $(2*k*t)/h^2 = 0.9975781249999998$ and the plot shown is most definitely incorrect. Perhaps this is an issue with my implementation?

7.5 "upwind" advection¶

Add code to solve the "upwind" advection equation.

The upwind scheme uses the left-derivative for discretization and produces results similar to Lax and Lax-Wendroff for the values of $\tau$ used in exercise 7.2. The solution decays for $\tau=0.015$, is stable for $\tau=0.02$, and explodes exponentially for $\tau > 0.0205$, so $\tau=0.02$ is just at the cusp of instability for the upwind scheme.

7.6 "leap-frog" advection¶

Use the Leap-Frog scheme for solving the advection equation.

The leap-frog scheme uses the centered-derivative for discretization of both terms and produces results similar to upwind. My implementation uses Lax-Wendroff for the first iteration, as it is a three time-level scheme. The solution retains the general structure for $\tau=0.015$, is stable for $\tau=0.02$, and explodes exponentially just like upwind for $\tau > 0.02$.

Appendix A, code base¶

using Plots
gr()

const L = 1. # System size
const c = 1. # wave speed

# t = timestep, n = number of grid points, mthd = integration method, tt = total time,
# pbc = periodic BCs (true/false), fq = frequency (for Dirichlet).
function advect(t, n; mthd, tt=1.0, tx=false, pbc=false, fq=10*pi)
    # Grid spacing.
    h = L/n

    k = c*t/(2*h) # Coefficient for all schemes.
    klw = 2*k^2 # Coefficient for Lax-Wendroff.

    # Initial conditions; integrate to total time.
    steps = Int(round(tt/t))

    sig = 0.1 # Width of Gaussian pulse.
    wn = pi/sig # Wave number.

    # x- and time-values for plotting.
    xvals = [h*i - L/2 for i in 0:(n-1)]
    tvals = [t*i for i in 0:(steps-1)]

    wv = zeros(steps, n)

    # Initial wave pulse if periodic BCs selected.
    if pbc 
        for (i,x) in enumerate(xvals)
            wv[1,i] = exp(-x^2/(2*sig^2)) * cos(wn*x)
        end
    end

    if tx
        xi = Int(ceil(n/8))
        wv[1, n-xi] = 1.0/(2*h)
    end

    return (mthd(wv, n, steps, k, pbc, fq, t, klw, h), xvals, tvals, n, t)
end

function ftcs(x...)
    wv, n, steps, k, pbc, fq, t = x

    for i in 2:steps
        if pbc
            # Periodic BCs
            for j in 1:n
                lft, rt = mod(j-2,n)+1, mod(j,n)+1
                wv[i,j] = wv[i-1,j] - k*(wv[i-1,lft] - wv[i-1,rt])
            end
        else
            # Dirichlet BCs
            wv[i,1] = sin(t*i*fq)
            for j in 2:(n-1)
                wv[i,j] = wv[i-1,j] - k*(wv[i-1,j-1] - wv[i-1,j+1])
            end
            wv[1,n] = 0
        end
    end

    return wv
end

function lax(x...)
    wv, n, steps, k, pbc, fq, t = x

    for i in 2:steps
        if pbc
            # Periodic BCs
            for j in 1:n
                lft, rt = mod(j-2,n)+1, mod(j,n)+1
                wv[i,j] = 0.5*(wv[i-1,rt] + wv[i-1,lft]) - k*(wv[i-1,rt] - wv[i-1,lft])
            end
        else
            # Dirichlet BCs
            wv[i,1] = sin(t*i*fq)
            for j in 2:(n-1)
                wv[i,j] = 0.5*(wv[i-1,j+1] + wv[i-1,j-1]) - k*(wv[i-1,j+1] - wv[i-1,j-1])
            end
            wv[1,n] = 0
        end
    end

    return wv
end

function wdf(x...)
    wv, n, steps, k, pbc, fq, t, klw = x

    for i in 2:steps
        if pbc
            # Periodic BCs
            for j in 1:n
                lft, rt = mod(j-2,n)+1, mod(j,n)+1
                wv[2,j] = wv[1,j] - k*(wv[1,rt] - wv[1,lft]) + klw*(wv[1,rt] + wv[1,lft] - 2*wv[1,j])
            end
        else
            # Dirichlet BCs
            wv[i,1] = sin(t*i*fq)
            for j in 2:(n-1)
                wv[i,j] = wv[i-1,j] - k*(wv[i-1,j+1] - wv[i-1,j-1]) + klw*(wv[i-1,j+1] + wv[i-1,j-1] - 2*wv[i-1,j])
            end
            wv[i,n] = 0
        end
    end

    return wv
end

function upwind(x...)
    wv, n, steps, k, pbc, fq, t, klw = x

    for i in 2:steps
        if pbc
            # Periodic BCs
            for j in 1:n
                wv[i,j] = wv[i-1,j] - 2*k*(wv[i-1,j] - wv[i-1,mod(j-2,n)+1])
            end
        else
            # Dirichlet BCs
            wv[i,1] = sin(t*i*fq)
            for j in 2:(n-1)
                wv[i,j] = wv[i-1,j] - 2*k*(wv[i-1,j] - wv[i-1,j-1])
            end
            wv[i,n] = 0
        end
    end

    return wv
end

function leapfrog(x...)
    wv, n, steps, k, pbc, fq, t, klw = x

    # One iteration of Lax-Wendroff to get leapfrog started.
    for j in 1:n
        lft, rt = mod(j-2,n)+1, mod(j,n)+1
        wv[2,j] = wv[1,j] - k*(wv[1,rt] - wv[1,lft]) + klw*(wv[1,rt] + wv[1,lft] - 2*wv[1,j])
    end

    for i in 3:steps
        if pbc
            # Periodic BCs
            for j in 1:n
                lft, rt = mod(j-2,n)+1, mod(j,n)+1
                wv[i,j] = wv[i-2,j] - 2*k*(wv[i-1,rt] - wv[i-1,lft])
            end
        else
            # Dirichlet BCs
            wv[i,1] = sin(t*i*fq)
            for j in 2:(n-1)
                wv[i,j] = wv[i-2,j] - 2*k*(wv[i-1,j+1] - wv[i-1,j-1])
            end
            wv[i,n] = 0
        end
    end

    return wv
end

function transport(x...)
    wv, n, steps, k, pbc, fq, t, klw, h = x

    # Coefficients for discretized transport eqn.
    k1, k2 = -c*t/h, k*t/h^2
    p, q = k2-k1, k1-2*k2+1

    s1, s2 = (c*t/h)^2, (2*k*t)/h^2

    if s1 <= s2 && s2 <= 1
        println("Solution expected to be stable:")
        println("(c*t/h)^2 = $s1 , (2*k*t)/h^2 = $s2")
    else
        println("Solution expected to be unstable")
        println("(c*t/h)^2 = $s1 , (2*k*t)/h^2 = $s2")
    end    

    for i in 2:steps
        for j in 1:n
            lft, rt = mod(j-2,n)+1, mod(j,n)+1
            a, b, c = wv[i-1,rt], wv[i-1,j], wv[i-1,lft]
            wv[i,j] = a*p + b*q + c*k2
        end
    end

    return wv
end     

function plt_dat(dat)
    wv, x, t, nstep, tstep = dat
    ttl = string("Advection for dt = ", string(tstep), " s, N = ", string(nstep))
    p1=surface(x, t, wv, title=ttl,
            xlabel=:"x", ylabel=:"time", zlabel=:"a(x,t)", 
            color=:Spectral_r, colorbar=false,
            st=:surface, camera=(25,50))
    p2=plot(x, wv[1,:], label="Initial")
    plot!(p2, x, wv[end,:], label="Final")
    plot(p1, p2, layout=2, size=(950,450))
end

function dir_gif(dat)
    wv, x, t, nstep, tstep = dat

    max_amp = 1.25
    min_amp = -1.25
    max_x = maximum(x)
    min_x = minimum(x)

    anim = @animate for i=1:2:Int(round(size(wv,1)))
        dt = "$(round(t[i], digits=4))"
        if length(dt) < 6
            dt = rpad(dt, 6, "0")
        end
        ttl = string("Sinusoidal dirichlet BC at time t = ", dt, " s")
        plot(size=(900,500), xlabel=:"x", ylabel=:"a(x)", xlims=(min_x, max_x), ylims=(min_amp, max_amp), title=ttl)
        plot!(x, wv[i, :], lw=4, label=:"")
    end every 5
    gif(anim, "advect.gif")
end
